{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "PSNs address many challenges in data analytics and is naturally interpretable.",
    "In a PSN, each node is an individual patient, and the distance (or edge) between 2 nodes corresponds to pairwise patient similarity for given features.",
    "PSNs naturally handle heterogeneous data, as any data type can be converted into a similarity network by defining similarity measures [24,25].",
    "A PSN generated based on a large cohort of patients will show several subgroups of patients who are tightly connected.",
    "If a new patient is located on the PSN, neighbors that have similar features with known risk or prognosis will inform clinicians of the potential risk and prognosis of the patient."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "PSNs naturally handle heterogeneous data, as any data type can be converted into a similarity network by defining similarity measures [24,25]."
  ]
}